This is a natural human language that's
used for what human languages are used

00:41:44.740 --> 00:41:50.530
for. And if we want to know where they got
their language from we can retrace the

00:41:50.710 --> 00:41:56.860
steps of the language further back when
these kids were four and five years old

00:41:57.040 --> 00:42:02.220
and ask who were the teenagers then when
they arrived at school?

00:42:02.400 --> 00:42:10.440
So we can look at the people who were 10
years older than them, when these guys,

00:42:10.620 --> 00:42:24.547
these are the cohort that arrived in the
1980s. So when they arrived, there were

00:42:24.547 --> 00:42:30.434
about 400 signers of Nicaraguan sign
language, again, 200 at the school. If you

00:42:30.434 --> 00:42:33.881
have an eye for it, you may be able to see
how, as we're going further and further

00:42:33.881 --> 00:42:39.156
back, the language is a little bit more
deliberate, the feedback is a little more

00:42:39.156 --> 00:42:44.214
explicit and the signs are bigger and
more symmetrical than more two-handed

00:42:44.214 --> 00:42:48.510
signs and lots of differences like that. A
lot of the work that I do is to try and

00:42:48.510 --> 00:42:50.974
quantify what those differences are.

00:42:51.881 --> 00:43:01.035
If you wanted to know who they got their
language from, to continue this retracing

00:43:01.035 --> 00:43:08.435
of the steps, when they arrived at the
school, the older people were these people

00:43:08.435 --> 00:43:19.370
who are 45 to 50 years old today and when
these people were four and five years old

00:43:19.370 --> 00:43:25.278
in the 1970s and they first came to the
school, there were no signers of

00:43:25.278 --> 00:43:31.973
Nicaraguan sign language and this is where
we reach the end of our retracing. Nobody

00:43:31.973 --> 00:43:37.731
taught these people to sign. The
teachers at the school used Spanish, which

00:43:37.731 --> 00:43:42.789
they couldn't hear and so this is where
Enocell begins with this cohort of 50

00:43:42.789 --> 00:43:46.862
pioneers. They took the gestures and
actions that they observed as raw

00:43:46.862 --> 00:43:49.618
materials and wove them into
a new language.

00:43:50.342 --> 00:43:55.589
So we have this incredible opportunity to
see how languages are born and evolve and

00:43:55.589 --> 00:43:59.863
the role that language learners play in
that evolution and I'm going to start with

00:43:59.863 --> 00:44:04.625
the language of this earliest first cohort
of signers and walk forward to the present

00:44:04.625 --> 00:44:07.319
day. And start with the most
fundamental pieces

00:44:07.319 --> 00:44:12.110
of the grammar that every language has,
the structure of the simple statement. So

00:44:12.290 --> 00:44:16.910
arguments and predicates, how do you show
who's doing what to whom? So in English

00:44:17.090 --> 00:44:22.380
for example, we use word order to do this.
So if you take a sentence like "A man taps

00:44:22.560 --> 00:44:27.100
a woman," and you change the order of the
words "A woman taps a man," you change

00:44:27.280 --> 00:44:32.380
who is doing the tapping and who gets
tapped. Now, other languages might stick

00:44:32.560 --> 00:44:36.920
inflectional endings on the end of the
verbs or even on the nouns to show which

00:44:37.100 --> 00:44:41.350
person is the tapper and which the tappee
is. And to figure this out, my colleagues

00:44:41.530 --> 00:44:47.590
and I use non-verb materials to illicit
sentences that can compare these different

00:44:47.770 --> 00:44:51.148
aspects of the sentence. So, I'll show you
how different signers

00:44:51.148 --> 00:44:53.099
respond to stimuli like these.

00:44:53.550 --> 00:45:01.310
So an event like this giving event or
this tapping event and here is what the

00:45:01.490 --> 00:45:05.330
first cohort sentence looks like. They
have a very strict noun, verb, noun, verb

00:45:05.510 --> 00:45:12.110
word order. So, to say that a woman taps a
man, you have woman, tap and man tapped.

00:45:12.290 --> 00:45:16.520
And here's what this looks like when a
first cohort signer signs it. So I want

00:45:16.700 --> 00:45:21.610
you to see how he produces that noun,
verb, noun, verb order for signing who

00:45:21.790 --> 00:45:28.730
tapped, the sign for woman, which is
produced like this and

00:45:28.730 --> 00:45:32.487
who is tapped, his sign for man.

00:45:32.487 --> 00:45:37.370
So, he's going to sign these nouns, man
and woman and in the neutral area in front

00:45:37.550 --> 00:45:41.470
of his chest, and note that there is this
movement in the verbs away from and toward

00:45:41.650 --> 00:45:45.920
the body the way they can reflect
iconically, the way that movement happens

00:45:46.100 --> 00:45:49.820
in the world but they are centered in the
signer's body. He keeps his body centered

00:45:50.000 --> 00:45:59.440
and neutral. And so, here is what it looks
like "woman, tap, man get tapped." So,

00:45:59.620 --> 00:46:03.850
this all very nice and clear and orderly.
But the interesting thing that it wasn't

00:46:04.030 --> 00:46:09.110
reproduced this way in the next second
cohorts. So, starting in about 1983 or

00:46:09.290 --> 00:46:14.710
'84, the second wave of kids who were
coming in took this direction in which

00:46:14.890 --> 00:46:20.060
signs are produced and started giving that
a job in the grammar. And what they did

00:46:20.240 --> 00:46:24.750
was they started modifying where they
produced their signs as a way of showing

00:46:24.930 --> 00:46:30.620
who did what to whom. So in this example
in the first panel, we have the words see

00:46:30.800 --> 00:46:35.500
and pay produced in this neutral area in
front of the chest and in the second panel

00:46:35.680 --> 00:46:40.160
you can see that the signs have been
modified so the direction is to the left.

00:46:40.340 --> 00:46:44.980
So, if these signs were together in one
sentence, produced by a second cohort

00:46:45.160 --> 00:46:51.160
signer, it would mean that the same person
was both see and paid. So, these

00:46:51.340 --> 00:46:55.910
inflections started out with the verbs
like this but soon after, in the mid 80s,

00:46:56.090 --> 00:47:01.960
you can also start producing nouns in
particular locations to link them to verbs

00:47:02.140 --> 00:47:06.440
and more recently, you can even use it
just to point to one location or another

00:47:06.620 --> 00:47:11.160
to refer to the person associated with
that location. So, now you're using these

00:47:11.340 --> 00:47:15.300
locations in space, not to talk about
where something happened but to show who's

00:47:15.480 --> 00:47:20.520
involved. So we'll see, here is an example
that a second cohort signer does and you

00:47:20.700 --> 00:47:22.910
can see how these developments
really changed the

00:47:22.910 --> 00:47:24.474
basic structure of the sentence.

00:47:25.160 --> 00:47:32.650
So, here is the woman giving to the man
event and you'll see you get the nouns now

00:47:32.830 --> 00:47:37.250
being produced in particular locations
that correspond with the direction of

00:47:37.430 --> 00:47:42.790
movement and the verbs to show you what
the object or recipient is. And notice

00:47:42.970 --> 00:47:47.280
that with the addition of the special
modification on the signs, we find there

00:47:47.460 --> 00:47:52.100
came in changes of the word, so now, the
verbs move to the end of the sentence. So

00:47:52.280 --> 00:47:56.190
you are going to see, first she talks
about, you remember those three people in

00:47:56.370 --> 00:47:59.550
that scene? So, she starts talking about
the woman on the right, just looking

00:47:59.730 --> 00:48:02.339
straight ahead, then she
touches her chest.

00:48:02.339 --> 00:48:07.280
That's a switch reference device and then
you'll see she does woman, man, your nouns

00:48:07.460 --> 00:48:16.550
and then gives, receive your verbs. Woman
look and then self, woman, man, give

00:48:16.730 --> 00:48:23.080
receive. And now, if we move to the third
cohort, we're going to see the

00:48:23.260 --> 00:48:27.074
introduction of the space you all use with
points linking the verbs

00:48:27.074 --> 00:48:28.862
with the doer and the done to.

00:48:29.110 --> 00:48:33.950
So this an event where a woman pushes
another woman, a woman in a black shirt

00:48:34.130 --> 00:48:40.380
and a woman in a green shirt. So he's
going to index the black shirt to his left

00:48:40.560 --> 00:48:44.740
and the woman in green to the right. And
then come the verbs, remember, they're at

00:48:44.920 --> 00:48:49.370
the end, push, be pushed and finally,
you'll see this verb respect at the end.

00:48:49.550 --> 00:48:53.940
And what I love about this example, the
respect sign here, is that even though

00:48:54.120 --> 00:48:58.370
respect isn't something that moves from
one person to another and nor is telling,

00:48:58.550 --> 00:49:01.670
here we're going to see the space and the
movement of the verb linking it to the

00:49:01.850 --> 00:49:07.030
nouns. So you can say green tells black
that black should show green some respect

00:49:07.210 --> 00:49:11.560
and you do that all with one
word using the space.

00:49:11.740 --> 00:49:22.450
So black, green, push, be pushed, respect,
see. Okay. So, we can measure this

00:49:22.630 --> 00:49:28.230
restructuring in many ways and here's one.
If you plot how frequently points are used

00:49:28.410 --> 00:49:32.530
in that way that shows who, rather than
where, you get this pattern. So, starting

00:49:32.710 --> 00:49:36.400
on the left with home signers who are deaf
people who are never exposed to a sign

00:49:36.580 --> 00:49:42.090
language and then the first, second and
third cohorts you can see that they all

00:49:42.270 --> 00:49:46.940
use points to where about the same amount
that something stay pretty stable. But

00:49:47.120 --> 00:49:51.950
this nominal use, this use that shows who,
that's linking the noun with the verbs,

00:49:52.130 --> 00:49:57.600
this has really increased with the second
and third cohorts of signers, so, the

00:49:57.780 --> 00:50:01.930
questions of, why this change?
And if children are so good at learning

00:50:02.110 --> 00:50:06.460
language and someone has already developed
a perfectly good way to mark subjects and

00:50:06.640 --> 00:50:11.970
objects, why didn't the second cohort just
learn to sign it the same way the first

00:50:12.150 --> 00:50:17.830
cohort had been doing it. I mean, it's one
thing to gradually to drop whom from your

00:50:18.010 --> 00:50:21.910
English but this is a total restructuring
of the language here. To answer that

00:50:22.090 --> 00:50:27.966
question, I think we really need to take
seriously, this idea of

00:50:27.966 --> 00:50:30.326
language as an organism.

00:50:31.730 --> 00:50:37.140
Language is an organism, so, this isn't
just a metaphor for when we say, a

00:50:37.320 --> 00:50:42.750
language is an abstract thing. It's
abstract but it's still real, it's a

00:50:42.930 --> 00:50:48.530
bundle of structured material and it's
self-replicating and we each live in a

00:50:48.710 --> 00:50:53.340
symbiotic relationship with our language,
like the microbes in our gut. We can't

00:50:53.520 --> 00:50:58.040
survive without it and it can't survive
without us. And language changes and

00:50:58.220 --> 00:51:04.880
adapts to the humans that host it. So, the
social network of people that learn it and

00:51:05.060 --> 00:51:09.580
pass it on are the environment in which
language evolves.

00:51:09.760 --> 00:51:13.710
Now, the different versions of Nicaraguan
sign language that we see signed by

00:51:13.890 --> 00:51:19.000
different age cohorts today represent this
living record of the evolutionary path of

00:51:19.180 --> 00:51:24.620
the language. And so, the way that I have
been doing my work, the way I have

00:51:24.800 --> 00:51:30.130
described is, I look at this slice today.
If you start with the 1970s with this

00:51:30.310 --> 00:51:34.760
figure over to the left and then you have
the first cohort coming in and in the 80s,

00:51:34.940 --> 00:51:41.700
the second cohort joins them and then the
third and fourth, we can look at today at

00:51:41.880 --> 00:51:44.217
the difference between the cohorts.

00:51:44.217 --> 00:51:50.650
But we can't forget that the action, the
moment of change, is over there. It's as

00:51:50.830 --> 00:51:55.030
we add each new wave and that's where the
language and that's when the language

00:51:55.210 --> 00:52:01.170
reproduces. So the first cohort builds the
language as children in the 70's and then

00:52:01.350 --> 00:52:07.290
they pass it on to this next cohort in the
80s and that second cohort acquires it

00:52:07.470 --> 00:52:10.654
with some fidelity but they
don't copy it exactly.

00:52:10.970 --> 00:52:16.380
And so, on in the 90s and today, and we
know these changes occurred when they're

00:52:16.560 --> 00:52:21.080
children because the path is
unidirectional. So, stuff can get passed

00:52:21.260 --> 00:52:26.600
on to later cohorts but not the other way.
It doesn't go back. So, things that adult

00:52:26.780 --> 00:52:31.220
initiate or learn, they would be the same
for everyone. And there are things like

00:52:31.400 --> 00:52:37.390
that that you see that are the same across
all of the cohorts. But these core aspects

00:52:37.570 --> 00:52:40.580
of the grammar how the sentence is
structured, how you do agreement, how you

00:52:40.760 --> 00:52:45.010
show who is doing what to whom. Those
kinds of things, they're changing in just

00:52:45.190 --> 00:52:49.019
that one direction and they don't get
passed on back up.

00:52:50.640 --> 00:52:55.790
So this chain from one to two then is
where that, where it got reinterpreted as

00:52:55.970 --> 00:53:01.440
who. So to take our question about why
change it, we have to really think about

00:53:01.620 --> 00:53:06.660
how languages replicate, what's the
mechanism that copies that code, the rules

00:53:06.840 --> 00:53:11.720
and patterns of Nicaraguan sign language
and passes it on to the next iteration of

00:53:11.900 --> 00:53:19.860
inner self because just because the
organism that say, 1980s NSL developed

00:53:20.040 --> 00:53:26.810
some cool characteristic, doesn't mean you
get to pass it on for free. If we don't

00:53:26.990 --> 00:53:30.950
have a really good understanding of the
mechanism of reproduction, what we'll

00:53:31.130 --> 00:53:35.890
start to see parallels between development
and evolution that don't actually explain

00:53:36.070 --> 00:53:37.589
the nature of the change.

00:53:37.589 --> 00:53:42.990
So, most of us are more familiar with
Lamarc's second law here, this idea that

00:53:43.170 --> 00:53:48.260
adaptations made by an organism in
response to its environment get inherited

00:53:48.440 --> 00:53:52.950
by its offspring. So the sons of the
blacksmith must have bigger biceps or the

00:53:53.130 --> 00:53:57.510
daughter of the giraffe gets a slightly
longer neck than her mother started with

00:53:57.690 --> 00:54:04.630
but Lemarc also had this first law that,
as much as we developed from simple cells

00:54:04.810 --> 00:54:11.320
to complex systems that all organisms have
a natural drive to complexify.

00:54:11.500 --> 00:54:15.040
And these are great ideas but they don't
worked out. They don't work out because

00:54:15.220 --> 00:54:19.120
now, we know that reproduction doesn't
work that way. You don't just pass down

00:54:19.300 --> 00:54:26.240
the useful stuff or the more complex stuff
or the exercised parts. And what we've

00:54:26.420 --> 00:54:30.380
learned from Darwin and since Darwin is
that we have to pay attention to

00:54:30.560 --> 00:54:35.770
reproduction and selection processes.
Organisms send along everything, they send

00:54:35.950 --> 00:54:40.750
down everything, not just the useful stuff
but they do it with variability and noise.

00:54:40.930 --> 00:54:44.710
So the environment is what's determining
what will survive.

00:54:44.890 --> 00:54:50.210
So now, we really have two evolutionary
processes on really, really different time

00:54:50.390 --> 00:54:55.680
scales. We've got human reproduction and
selection on one hand and language

00:54:55.860 --> 00:55:00.520
reproduction and selection on the other.
It's not that one recapitulates the other,

00:55:00.700 --> 00:55:04.920
it's each of them is evolving and is
shaped by the processes of reproduction

00:55:05.100 --> 00:55:10.470
and selection. In human reproduction, we
pass on what are the patterns we can learn

00:55:10.650 --> 00:55:15.880
and it may be very slowly and very long
ago that more effective and more powerful

00:55:16.060 --> 00:55:18.671
pattern-learning devices would prevail.

00:55:19.290 --> 00:55:24.910
But we all came into the world with brains
that are a product of that process. On the

00:55:25.090 --> 00:55:29.830
other hand, when language is reproduced,
they send out all these accumulated

00:55:30.010 --> 00:55:34.430
symbols and patterns of combinations but
it's a blurry and limited signal

00:55:34.430 --> 00:55:39.850
and it's just the output of someone's own
language and it isn't copied perfectly. In

00:55:40.030 --> 00:55:44.410
the process of selection, it's not the
useful stuff but the learnable parts of

00:55:44.590 --> 00:55:52.570
the language that survive. So what we've
got then, is this co-evolution of humans

00:55:52.750 --> 00:55:57.680
and their languages. Each of them is
serving as the environment for the other

00:55:57.860 --> 00:56:05.900
and each cannot survive without the other.
The thing is though, that we don't set out

00:56:06.080 --> 00:56:11.030
to create languages, to grow languages,
this isn't done with an intention to make

00:56:11.210 --> 00:56:17.070
a code. Humans grow languages because our
social connection is so critical. When we

00:56:17.250 --> 00:56:22.780
pass a language from one generation to the
next, the goal isn't to create something

00:56:22.960 --> 00:56:24.886
or to organize your message.

00:56:25.450 --> 00:56:31.460
The goal is to connect and the drive is a
social one. The idea is to get your

00:56:31.640 --> 00:56:35.450
message into someone else's mind and to
understand what message someone else is

00:56:35.630 --> 00:56:39.980
sending to your mind. And in that process
of communicating back and forth and

00:56:40.160 --> 00:56:44.940
actually forth and forth, that's how we
use the fabric of language with the

00:56:45.120 --> 00:56:49.679
machinery of our minds.
So, thank you very much.

